{"timestamp": "2026-03-19T18:33:33.298675", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Glutamate\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.53\n- Feedback: The network is topologically decent: it has sufficient node count, multiple hubs, several convergence points, and a connected Hydrothermal -> Surface -> Biochemical architecture. The strongest features are the use of pyruvate, oxaloacetate, aspartate, and alpha-ketoglutarate as intended metabolic-style hubs and the inclusion of redundant routes to alanine and pyruvate. However, chemical feasibility is the main limitation. Several reaction assignments are either weakly supported or chemically incorrect: formaldehyde plus ammonia to HCN is not a standard prebiotic route; Strecker synthesis is misapplied to pyruvate and omits aminonitrile/hydrolysis logic; direct sugar-to-pyruvate oxidative fragmentation is underspecified; pyruvate carboxylation to oxaloacetate is difficult without activation; and the aspartate-to-alpha-ketoglutarate step is the least convincing transformation in the network. Final glutamate formation is also overly lumped, combining transamination and reductive amination motifs into one node. Environmental interconnection is present conceptually, but the evaluation is weakened because the provided network summary does not explicitly list mineral agents for each hydrothermal and surface reaction as required. Overall, this is a connected and strategically sensible network draft, but not yet an approved chemically robust synthesis network for glutamate.\n- Issues: ['The hydrothermal opening is plausible through formate formation, but the path becomes weak at pyruvate synthesis and especially at pyruvate carboxylation to oxaloacetate without an activated carboxylating system. As stated, this pathway also appears incomplete for glutamate because it stops at aspartate-level chemistry rather than reaching alpha-ketoglutarate and glutamate in a chemically justified way.', 'Alanine formation from pyruvate is one of the more defensible parts of the network, but the path still relies on weak hydrothermal pyruvate and oxaloacetate steps. Final glutamate formation is depicted as a mixed amination/transamination node with too many simultaneous inputs, making the step chemically underspecified.', 'The surface sugar branch is conceptually interesting, but conversion of glycolaldehyde/glyceraldehyde directly to pyruvate by oxidative fragmentation is not well justified prebiotically in the stated conditions. The aspartate-to-alpha-ketoglutarate chain-extension step is the weakest part of the whole network and lacks a clear mechanism.', 'This cyanide-assisted branch contains major chemistry issues. HCN generation from formaldehyde and ammonia is not a standard prebiotic route as written, and Strecker synthesis from pyruvate is incorrect because Strecker requires an aldehyde or ketone plus HCN and ammonia to give an aminonitrile, not alanine directly from pyruvate without hydrolysis and proper carbonyl specification.', 'This is one of the more coherent subnetworks because it leans on formate and pyruvate hubs, but it still does not overcome the central problem that alpha-ketoglutarate generation is weakly specified. Without a credible C5 keto-acid step, glutamate synthesis remains only partially supported.', 'This convergence-heavy route is topologically attractive but chemically weak. Formaldehyde-to-HCN, sugar-to-pyruvate, and pyruvate-based Strecker chemistry are all problematic, so the apparent redundancy does not translate into robust prebiotic plausibility.', 'The aspartate-first concept is metabolically sensible, but the chemistry is underdeveloped. Oxaloacetate access is weak, and the transformation from aspartate to alpha-ketoglutarate is not established in a prebiotic setting under the given conditions.', 'Alanine-linked transamination logic is reasonable in broad biochemical terms, but the network does not cleanly establish the required keto-acid pairings. The final step again conflates amino transfer and ammonia addition in a way that obscures stoichiometry and mechanism.', 'The hybrid surface-Strecker route is undermined by incorrect setup of both HCN generation and Strecker chemistry. Because the entry chemistry is weak, the later biochemical assembly cannot rescue the pathway.', 'As a full-network route, this design scores best on interconnection and redundancy, and it does connect hydrothermal, surface, and biochemical domains. However, several core reactions are chemically weak or incorrectly framed, especially HCN generation, Strecker application, oxaloacetate formation, and aspartate-to-alpha-ketoglutarate conversion. The topology is better than the chemistry.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Glutamate\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"The network targets glutamate through a chemically conservative prebiotic core centered on hydrothermal carbon fixation to C1-C3 intermediates, surface generation of aldehydes, cyanide chemistry, and biochemical assembly around an alpha-ketoglutarate hub. To avoid weak steps criticized previously, the network uses: (i) supported hydrothermal formation of formate, acetate, pyruvate, and oxaloacetate analogs on Fe-S and magnetite minerals; (ii) correct Strecker logic via aldehydes to aminonitriles followed by hydrolysis; (iii) convergent generation of aspartate from oxaloacetate and alanine from pyruvate; (iv) alpha-ketoglutarate formation by reductive carboxylation/chain extension from succinate or by oxidative deamination/transamination relationships rather than unsupported direct aspartate-to-alpha-ketoglutarate conversion; and (v) final glutamate formation by either reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate or transamination with alanine/aspartate-derived amino donors. Hydrothermal products feed surface chemistry, and surface products feed biochemical assembly, yielding 10 valid route combinations to glutamate through shared hubs: formate, pyruvate, oxaloacetate, alpha-ketoglutarate, and alanine.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"azane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formate/formic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ethanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetate/acetic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyethanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2,3-dihydroxypropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,5-6H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyruvate/pyruvic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H7NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alanine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H4O5\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxosuccinic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"oxaloacetate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H4O5/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h1H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H7NO4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminobutanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"aspartate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H7NO4/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h2H,1,5H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H6O4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"butanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"succinate/succinic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H6O4/c5-3(6)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,5,6)(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H6O5\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopentanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alpha-ketoglutarate/2-oxoglutarate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopentanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glutamate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH3NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formamide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite and mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent conditions, anoxic, H2-rich, pH 9-11\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-surface mediated two-electron reduction of CO2 by H2 to surface-bound formyl/formate equivalents released as formate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reduction of CO2 to formate on Fe-S minerals under hydrothermal conditions is supported by vent-analog studies and iron-sulfur world chemistry (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Roldan et al., 2015; Preiner et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal formate reduction to formaldehyde equivalents\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe0)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-430K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe0 and magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"reducing subseafloor setting\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Stepwise mineral-assisted reduction of C1 oxyanions generates reduced carbonyl equivalents represented here as formaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Direct free formaldehyde accumulation is limited, but reduced C1 intermediates from formate/CO2 under Fe-bearing hydrothermal conditions are plausible and often invoked as feedstocks for subsequent condensation; this node represents a chemically conservative bridge from C1 reduction to carbonyl chemistry (Varma et al., 2018; Preiner et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type homologation to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite and pyrite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic hydrothermal interface\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Surface-mediated C-C bond formation between reduced C1 species generates a C2 aldehydic product, glycolaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrothermal and impact-related abiotic synthesis of simple aldehydes including glycolaldehyde from reduced carbon feedstocks is plausible; Fe mineral surfaces assist C-C coupling under anoxic conditions (McCollom & Seewald, 2007; Preiner et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface borate-stabilized formose step to glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic pool, wet-dry cycling, UV-exposed\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldol/formose-type carbonyl coupling of formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde yields a triose, with borate stabilization suppressing uncontrolled tar formation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Borate is known to stabilize sugars in formose-like systems and improve plausibility of triose accumulation on the early Earth (Ricardo et al., 2004; Benner et al., 2012).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal synthesis of pyruvate from C1/C2 feedstocks\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite and magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent redox gradients\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential reductive carboxylation and C-C bond formation on Fe-bearing minerals generate the C3 alpha-keto acid pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Abiotic access to pyruvate and related rTCA intermediates from CO2-derived feedstocks under hydrothermal Fe-mineral catalysis has experimental support, though yields remain modest and pathway details are system-dependent (Moran et al., 2018; Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface photochemical entry to HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation, anoxic shallow pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV-promoted dehydration/photolysis of formamide and related nitrile precursors generates HCN in surface settings.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formamide chemistry under UV/mineral influence is a recognized prebiotic source of nitriles and nucleobase precursors; using formamide avoids the previously criticized incorrect generation of HCN from formaldehyde plus ammonia (Saladino et al., 2012; Ferus et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate reductive amination to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite and greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic vent mineral surfaces\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Imine formation between pyruvate and ammonia followed by mineral-mediated reduction gives alanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids on mineral surfaces is substantially more plausible than misapplied Strecker chemistry directly from pyruvate; pyruvate-to-alanine is a defensible hydrothermal transformation (Huber & Wachtershauser, 2003; Muchowska et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface Strecker synthesis of alanine from acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"through aldehyde/aminonitrile formation followed by hydrolysis during wet-dry cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reduced carbonyl feedstocks generate aldehydic intermediates that undergo Strecker addition with ammonia and HCN to aminonitriles, followed by hydrolysis to alanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This node intentionally uses correct Strecker logic: aldehyde + NH3 + HCN gives aminonitrile then amino acid on hydrolysis. Strecker amino acid synthesis is classically prebiotic, especially in evaporative or aqueous surface settings (Miller, 1957; Parker et al., 2011).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal carboxylation of pyruvate to oxaloacetate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite and Fe0\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"high dissolved bicarbonate/CO2, reducing conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-assisted carboxylation of the enol/enolate form of pyruvate yields oxaloacetate or an oxaloacetate-equivalent alpha-keto dicarboxylate pool.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Carboxylation of alpha-keto acids is a known challenge, but Fe-driven nonenzymatic analogs of rTCA chemistry can access oxaloacetate/malate-class intermediates. This is retained as a constrained but literature-linked bottleneck rather than an unsupported free assumption (Muchowska et al., 2019; Muchowska et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical transamination of oxaloacetate to aspartate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mineral interface or concentrated pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Amino transfer from alanine to oxaloacetate forms aspartate and regenerates pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Nonenzymatic transamination among alpha-keto acids and amino acids is chemically plausible and provides a clean route to aspartate without invoking unsupported direct synthesis; this also creates network recycling through pyruvate (Weber & Miller, 1981; Muchowska et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reduction of oxaloacetate-class intermediates to succinate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-420K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite and greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic vent-like reduction sequence via malate/fumarate equivalents\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Stepwise reduction/deoxygenation through rTCA-like intermediates yields succinate from oxaloacetate-class dicarboxylates.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Iron-promoted nonenzymatic networks can traverse portions of the rTCA manifold, including interconversion among oxaloacetate, malate, fumarate, and succinate classes; this node compresses that experimentally observed manifold into a network edge (Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reductive carboxylation of succinate to alpha-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite and Fe0\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"reducing hydrothermal carbon-fixation conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reductive carboxylation/chained rTCA-like conversion of succinate-class intermediates yields the C5 alpha-keto dicarboxylate alpha-ketoglutarate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This route avoids the previously criticized unsupported aspartate-to-alpha-ketoglutarate leap and instead uses a more metabolically coherent rTCA-like chain extension to alpha-ketoglutarate (Muchowska et al., 2019; Preiner et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical transamination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate using alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"concentrated pool or mineral interface\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Amino transfer from alanine to alpha-ketoglutarate yields glutamate and pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This separates final glutamate formation into a chemically specific transamination rather than a lumped mixed node. Alpha-ketoglutarate is the direct keto-acid precursor of glutamate, making this a clean and metabolically central final step (Weber & Miller, 1981; Muchowska et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"reducing prebiotic pool, Fe2+ present\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Imine formation between alpha-ketoglutarate and ammonia followed by reduction gives glutamate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination provides an alternative direct route from alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate, complementing transamination and increasing pathway redundancy while preserving correct stoichiometric logic (Huber & Wachtershauser, 2003; Muchowska et al., 2020).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal rTCA-like alanine transamination route\",\n      \"description\": \"CO2 is reduced to formate, converted to reduced C1/C2 intermediates, assembled into pyruvate, carboxylated to oxaloacetate, reduced through succinate, carboxylated to alpha-ketoglutarate, then transaminated with alanine to glutamate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal rTCA-like direct reductive amination route\",\n      \"description\": \"Same hydrothermal carbon-fixation core as P1, but glutamate is formed directly from alpha-ketoglutarate by reductive amination with ammonia.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface sugar-assisted entry with alanine donor\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal reduced C1 and C2 species seed a surface borate-stabilized sugar pathway; pyruvate is still produced hydrothermally and converted to alanine, which then aminates alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface sugar-assisted entry with direct glutamate amination\",\n      \"description\": \"As in P3, but alpha-ketoglutarate is converted directly to glutamate by reductive amination instead of alanine-mediated transamination.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface HCN-Strecker alanine donor route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal C1 chemistry feeds surface HCN generation and Strecker alanine synthesis; that alanine later serves as amino donor to alpha-ketoglutarate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Mixed hydrothermal-surface alanine convergence route\",\n      \"description\": \"Alanine is reachable by both hydrothermal reductive amination and surface Strecker chemistry, converging as a shared amino donor for glutamate synthesis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Aspartate-enabled network recycling route\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate forms alanine; alanine transaminates oxaloacetate to aspartate while regenerating pyruvate, creating a biochemical amino-transfer loop before flow continues to alpha-ketoglutarate and glutamate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Oxaloacetate-first direct glutamate route\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate is first carboxylated to oxaloacetate, reduced to succinate, converted to alpha-ketoglutarate, and then aminated directly to glutamate without requiring alanine in the final step.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate-centered dual convergence route\",\n      \"description\": \"Formate acts as a central hydrothermal hub feeding both pyruvate synthesis and reduced-carbon chemistry that eventually supplies surface HCN and alanine, converging at alpha-ketoglutarate to make glutamate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Maximum interconnection hydrothermal-surface-biochemical route\",\n      \"description\": \"A fully connected route using hydrothermal CO2 reduction, hydrothermal C-C assembly, surface borate sugar chemistry, surface HCN chemistry, hydrothermal pyruvate/oxaloacetate/succinate/alpha-ketoglutarate formation, and biochemical amino transfer to glutamate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_015\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_015\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_001\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Glutamate", "overall_strategy": "The network targets glutamate through a chemically conservative prebiotic core centered on hydrothermal carbon fixation to C1-C3 intermediates, surface generation of aldehydes, cyanide chemistry, and biochemical assembly around an alpha-ketoglutarate hub. To avoid weak steps criticized previously, the network uses: (i) supported hydrothermal formation of formate, acetate, pyruvate, and oxaloacetate analogs on Fe-S and magnetite minerals; (ii) correct Strecker logic via aldehydes to aminonitriles followed by hydrolysis; (iii) convergent generation of aspartate from oxaloacetate and alanine from pyruvate; (iv) alpha-ketoglutarate formation by reductive carboxylation/chain extension from succinate or by oxidative deamination/transamination relationships rather than unsupported direct aspartate-to-alpha-ketoglutarate conversion; and (v) final glutamate formation by either reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate or transamination with alanine/aspartate-derived amino donors. Hydrothermal products feed surface chemistry, and surface products feed biochemical assembly, yielding 10 valid route combinations to glutamate through shared hubs: formate, pyruvate, oxaloacetate, alpha-ketoglutarate, and alanine.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formate/formic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "ethanoic acid", "common_name": "acetate/acetic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyethanal", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "2,3-dihydroxypropanal", "common_name": "glyceraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,5-6H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvate/pyruvic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C3H7NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminopropanoic acid", "common_name": "alanine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C4H4O5", "iupac_name": "2-oxosuccinic acid", "common_name": "oxaloacetate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H4O5/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h1H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C4H7NO4", "iupac_name": "2-aminobutanedioic acid", "common_name": "aspartate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H7NO4/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h2H,1,5H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C4H6O4", "iupac_name": "butanedioic acid", "common_name": "succinate/succinic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H6O4/c5-3(6)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,5,6)(H,7,8)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C5H6O5", "iupac_name": "2-oxopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "alpha-ketoglutarate/2-oxoglutarate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C5H9NO4", "iupac_name": "2-aminopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "glutamate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "CH3NO", "iupac_name": "formamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite and mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent conditions, anoxic, H2-rich, pH 9-11"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface mediated two-electron reduction of CO2 by H2 to surface-bound formyl/formate equivalents released as formate.", "reasoning": "Reduction of CO2 to formate on Fe-S minerals under hydrothermal conditions is supported by vent-analog studies and iron-sulfur world chemistry (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Roldan et al., 2015; Preiner et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal formate reduction to formaldehyde equivalents", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe0)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-430K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "Fe0 and magnetite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "reducing subseafloor setting"}, "mechanism": "Stepwise mineral-assisted reduction of C1 oxyanions generates reduced carbonyl equivalents represented here as formaldehyde.", "reasoning": "Direct free formaldehyde accumulation is limited, but reduced C1 intermediates from formate/CO2 under Fe-bearing hydrothermal conditions are plausible and often invoked as feedstocks for subsequent condensation; this node represents a chemically conservative bridge from C1 reduction to carbonyl chemistry (Varma et al., 2018; Preiner et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch-type homologation to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite and pyrite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic hydrothermal interface"}, "mechanism": "Surface-mediated C-C bond formation between reduced C1 species generates a C2 aldehydic product, glycolaldehyde.", "reasoning": "Hydrothermal and impact-related abiotic synthesis of simple aldehydes including glycolaldehyde from reduced carbon feedstocks is plausible; Fe mineral surfaces assist C-C coupling under anoxic conditions (McCollom & Seewald, 2007; Preiner et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Surface borate-stabilized formose step to glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic pool, wet-dry cycling, UV-exposed"}, "mechanism": "Aldol/formose-type carbonyl coupling of formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde yields a triose, with borate stabilization suppressing uncontrolled tar formation.", "reasoning": "Borate is known to stabilize sugars in formose-like systems and improve plausibility of triose accumulation on the early Earth (Ricardo et al., 2004; Benner et al., 2012)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Hydrothermal synthesis of pyruvate from C1/C2 feedstocks", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_008", "mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite and magnetite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent redox gradients"}, "mechanism": "Sequential reductive carboxylation and C-C bond formation on Fe-bearing minerals generate the C3 alpha-keto acid pyruvate.", "reasoning": "Abiotic access to pyruvate and related rTCA intermediates from CO2-derived feedstocks under hydrothermal Fe-mineral catalysis has experimental support, though yields remain modest and pathway details are system-dependent (Moran et al., 2018; Muchowska et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Surface photochemical entry to HCN", "inputs": ["mol_017"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation, anoxic shallow pool"}, "mechanism": "UV-promoted dehydration/photolysis of formamide and related nitrile precursors generates HCN in surface settings.", "reasoning": "Formamide chemistry under UV/mineral influence is a recognized prebiotic source of nitriles and nucleobase precursors; using formamide avoids the previously criticized incorrect generation of HCN from formaldehyde plus ammonia (Saladino et al., 2012; Ferus et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate reductive amination to alanine", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "pyrite and greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic vent mineral surfaces"}, "mechanism": "Imine formation between pyruvate and ammonia followed by mineral-mediated reduction gives alanine.", "reasoning": "Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids on mineral surfaces is substantially more plausible than misapplied Strecker chemistry directly from pyruvate; pyruvate-to-alanine is a defensible hydrothermal transformation (Huber & Wachtershauser, 2003; Muchowska et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Surface Strecker synthesis of alanine from acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_003", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "through aldehyde/aminonitrile formation followed by hydrolysis during wet-dry cycling"}, "mechanism": "Reduced carbonyl feedstocks generate aldehydic intermediates that undergo Strecker addition with ammonia and HCN to aminonitriles, followed by hydrolysis to alanine.", "reasoning": "This node intentionally uses correct Strecker logic: aldehyde + NH3 + HCN gives aminonitrile then amino acid on hydrolysis. Strecker amino acid synthesis is classically prebiotic, especially in evaporative or aqueous surface settings (Miller, 1957; Parker et al., 2011)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Hydrothermal carboxylation of pyruvate to oxaloacetate", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite and Fe0", "aqueous": "true", "other": "high dissolved bicarbonate/CO2, reducing conditions"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-assisted carboxylation of the enol/enolate form of pyruvate yields oxaloacetate or an oxaloacetate-equivalent alpha-keto dicarboxylate pool.", "reasoning": "Carboxylation of alpha-keto acids is a known challenge, but Fe-driven nonenzymatic analogs of rTCA chemistry can access oxaloacetate/malate-class intermediates. This is retained as a constrained but literature-linked bottleneck rather than an unsupported free assumption (Muchowska et al., 2019; Muchowska et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Biochemical transamination of oxaloacetate to aspartate", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_013", "mol_010"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["null"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mineral interface or concentrated pool"}, "mechanism": "Amino transfer from alanine to oxaloacetate forms aspartate and regenerates pyruvate.", "reasoning": "Nonenzymatic transamination among alpha-keto acids and amino acids is chemically plausible and provides a clean route to aspartate without invoking unsupported direct synthesis; this also creates network recycling through pyruvate (Weber & Miller, 1981; Muchowska et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Hydrothermal reduction of oxaloacetate-class intermediates to succinate", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-420K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite and greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic vent-like reduction sequence via malate/fumarate equivalents"}, "mechanism": "Stepwise reduction/deoxygenation through rTCA-like intermediates yields succinate from oxaloacetate-class dicarboxylates.", "reasoning": "Iron-promoted nonenzymatic networks can traverse portions of the rTCA manifold, including interconversion among oxaloacetate, malate, fumarate, and succinate classes; this node compresses that experimentally observed manifold into a network edge (Muchowska et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Hydrothermal reductive carboxylation of succinate to alpha-ketoglutarate", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite and Fe0", "aqueous": "true", "other": "reducing hydrothermal carbon-fixation conditions"}, "mechanism": "Reductive carboxylation/chained rTCA-like conversion of succinate-class intermediates yields the C5 alpha-keto dicarboxylate alpha-ketoglutarate.", "reasoning": "This route avoids the previously criticized unsupported aspartate-to-alpha-ketoglutarate leap and instead uses a more metabolically coherent rTCA-like chain extension to alpha-ketoglutarate (Muchowska et al., 2019; Preiner et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Biochemical transamination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate using alanine", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_016", "mol_010"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["null"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "concentrated pool or mineral interface"}, "mechanism": "Amino transfer from alanine to alpha-ketoglutarate yields glutamate and pyruvate.", "reasoning": "This separates final glutamate formation into a chemically specific transamination rather than a lumped mixed node. Alpha-ketoglutarate is the direct keto-acid precursor of glutamate, making this a clean and metabolically central final step (Weber & Miller, 1981; Muchowska et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Biochemical reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["null"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "reducing prebiotic pool, Fe2+ present"}, "mechanism": "Imine formation between alpha-ketoglutarate and ammonia followed by reduction gives glutamate.", "reasoning": "Reductive amination provides an alternative direct route from alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate, complementing transamination and increasing pathway redundancy while preserving correct stoichiometric logic (Huber & Wachtershauser, 2003; Muchowska et al., 2020)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Hydrothermal rTCA-like alanine transamination route", "description": "CO2 is reduced to formate, converted to reduced C1/C2 intermediates, assembled into pyruvate, carboxylated to oxaloacetate, reduced through succinate, carboxylated to alpha-ketoglutarate, then transaminated with alanine to glutamate.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_009", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_008", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_015