rongest chemistry. It leverages all environments well, yet includes the flawed HCN/formamide/Strecker branch and the weak alpha-ketoglutarate-forming step, keeping confidence below approval.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Retain the broad interconnection while pruning chemically problematic HCN steps\",\n        \"Correct Strecker chemistry with explicit acetaldehyde and aminonitrile intermediates\",\n        \"Focus the integrated pathway on the hydrothermal alanine branch plus biochemical transamination\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"best_pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n  \"overall_confidence\": 0.74,\n  \"network_feedback\": \"The network is strong topologically: it has sufficient size, clear hubs, multiple convergence points, and good Hydrothermal to Surface to Biochemical interconnection. Glutamate is reached by chemically sensible terminal steps, especially via transamination from alpha-ketoglutarate. The main limitations are chemical, not architectural. Several hydrothermal core steps are plausible in broad outline but underspecified or optimistic, especially formate to formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde formation by hydrothermal homologation, pyruvate carboxylation to oxaloacetate, reduction of oxaloacetate-class intermediates to succinate, and most importantly reductive carboxylation of succinate to alpha-ketoglutarate. The surface HCN branch has a more serious correctness issue: alanine Strecker synthesis is written from HCN, NH3, and formaldehyde, but requires acetaldehyde and ideally an aminonitrile intermediate; formamide to HCN is also weakly framed. Thus the network is connected and strategically coherent, but not yet approved because the C5 ketoacid-forming chemistry and one surface branch are not sufficiently secure.\",\n  \"approved\": false,\n  \"hub_quality\": 0.9,\n  \"convergence_quality\": 0.86\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluatio